The '''1804 rebellion in [[Mtiuleti]]''' was a conflict in the former [[Kingdom of Kartli-Kakheti]] (eastern [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]), at that time part of the [[Georgia Governorate]] of the [[Russian Empire]]. It was the first major Georgian rebellion directed against the [[Georgia within the Russian Empire|Russian administration]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} 

==Background==
In 1801, the Russians capitalized on the moment, and annexed the Kingdom of Kartli-Kakheti. The entity was then reduced to the status of a [[guberniya|Russian region]] (Georgia Governorate). Though the Russian administration brought some peace, Kartli-Kakheti remained troubled.{{sfn|Suny|1994|pages=68-70}}{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|pages=263-264}}

==Rebellion==
It broke out at a vulnerable spot, to the west of the [[Darial Gorge|Darial Pass]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} A number of local [[Ossetians]] had complained about the grain and meat demands of [[Cossacks]] stationed in the area.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} They were thrown into a pit.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} The Cossacks then proceeded to punish more locals; peasants were put to forced labour, two men were killed by whip lashing, women were mistreated, and cattle was worked to death.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}}

The people of the [[Aragvi River|Aragvi valley]] then attacked the troops of Dmitri Mikhailovich Volkonsky, killing several of them.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} They then proceeded to occupy several of the forts on the nearby main road.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} In the summer of 1804, 4,000 [[Georgians|Georgian]] and Ossetian rebels requested [[Prince Parnaoz of Georgia|Prince Parnaoz]] to lead them.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} On 3 August 1804, the rebels and Russian forces clashed at Lomisi; the Russian forces reportedly only escaped defeat due to the "timidity" of the Kakhetian nobles and the return of Russian General [[Pavel Tsitsianov]], who had just [[Siege of Erivan (1804)|unsuccessfully besieged Erivan]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} The rebellion was eventually crushed; hundreds of highlanders were [[bayonet]]ed or imprisoned.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}} It would take eight years before more anti-Russian violence erupted.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=263}}{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=70}}

A part of the Georgian nobles participated in the 1804 Mtiuleti rebellion.{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=70}}

