The '''San Remo Oil Agreement''' was an agreement between Britain and France signed at the [[San Remo conference]] on 24 April 1920.<ref>{{cite web|title=1920 League of Nations Treaty Series | publisher=WorldLII |url =http://www.worldlii.org/int/other/LNTSer/1920/17.html}}</ref> As a result of this agreement, the French [[Total S.A.|Compagnie Française de Petroles]] (CFP){{efn|group=lower-alpha|Initially held by the French government and transferred on creation of CFP in 1924<ref name=GT-DEX-1920-78>{{cite web|title=MILESTONES: 1921-1936, The 1928 Red Line Agreemen |url=https://history.state.gov/milestones/1921-1936/RedLine |work=US Department of State |accessdate=18 August 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729164126/http://history.state.gov/milestones/1921-1936/RedLine |archivedate=29 July 2012 |df= }}</ref>}} acquired a 25% share in the [[Iraq Petroleum Company|Turkish Petroleum Company]] (TPC). The other shareholders were the [[Anglo-Persian Oil Company]] (APOC) with 47.5%, the [[Anglo Saxon Petroleum | Anglo Saxon Petroleum Co]] 22.5% and the remaining 5% [[Calouste Gulbenkian]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Zedalis|first=Rex J.|title=The Legal Dimensions of Oil and Gas in Iraq: Current Reality and Future Prospects|year=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page =264|isbn=9780521766616 }}</ref>
==Background== On 19 March 1914, the British and German governments had signed an agreement whereby the interest of [[National Bank of Turkey]] in TPC was transferred to APOC. The newly reconstituted TPC then applied for a concession for Mesopotamian oil which was granted subject to various conditions at which point [[World War I]] intervened. In December 1918, the British expropriated the 25% share of Deutsche Bank in TPC.<ref name = Earle>Earle, Edward Meade 1924 The Turkish Petroleum Company:A Study in Oleaginous Diplomacy Political Science Quarterly, vol. 39, no. 2, pp. 265-279</ref>{{rp|269}}
It was this latter share that was ultimately to be given to the French under the San Remo oil agreement. There were prior abortive attempts at an agreement, preliminary and then final version of the Long-Bérenger Agreement,<ref name = Marian>Marian Kent 1976 Oil & Empire:British Policy and Mesopotamian Oil 1900-1920 Macmillan Press {{ISBN|9781349020812}}</ref>{{rp |148 & 172}} then the Greenwood-Bérenger Agreement before the final San Remo version. All versions can be seen at.<ref name ="Marian"/>{{rp|172–8}}
The agreement delimited the oil interests in [[Russia]] and [[Romania]], British ([[British Mandate of Mesopotamia]]) and French colonies. The initial agreement takes the names of the British petroleum minister, Sir Walter Long, and the French petroleum minister, Henri Bérenger, who negotiated the agreement.<ref name=Gareth>G. Gareth Jones (1977). The British Government and the Oil Companies 1912–1924: the Search for an Oil Policy. The Historical Journal, 20, pp 647-672 doi:10.1017/S0018246X00011286</ref>
